In mathematics, a '''nullform''' of a [[vector space]] [[Group action (mathematics)|acted]] on [[linear map|linearly]] by a [[group (mathematics)|group]] is a vector on which all [[Invariant theory|invariants]] of the group vanish. Nullforms were introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Hilbert|year=1893|authorlink=David Hilbert}}. {{harvs|last=Dieudonné|last2=Carrell|year1=1970|year2=1971|loc2=p.57}}.

