In [[mathematics]], an '''antifundamental representation''' of a [[Lie group]] is the complex conjugate of the [[fundamental representation]],<ref>{{citation|title=The Standard Model: A Primer|first1=Cliff|last1=Burgess|first2=Guy|last2=Moore|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139460460|page=492|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PLYECqs2geEC&pg=PA492|date=2006-12-07}}.</ref> although the distinction between the fundamental and the antifundamental representation is a matter of convention. However, these two are often non-equivalent, because each of them is a [[complex representation]].

